<Layout title="Pluto's Geology" description="Nitrogen ice plains, water-ice mountains, and the surprising surface of Pluto.">
  <h1>The Surface of Pluto</h1>
  <p>
    Before 2015, Pluto was little more than a blurry dot. The New Horizons flyby
    revealed a stunningly varied and surprisingly young surface, with towering
    mountains, glacial plains, and possible ice volcanoes.
  </p>

  <!-- Sputnik Planitia image deliberately missing alt (image-alt) -->
  <figure>
    <img src="/images/pluto-sputnik-planitia.jpg" width="520" class="content-img" />
    <figcaption>
      High-resolution view of Pluto, dominated by the bright Sputnik Planitia
      ice plain.
    </figcaption>
  </figure>

  <h2>Sputnik Planitia: a sea of ice</h2>
  <p>
    The western lobe of Pluto's "heart" is Sputnik Planitia, a vast basin filled
    with frozen nitrogen. Its surface is divided into polygonal cells, each tens
    of kilometres across, created as the nitrogen ice slowly convects — warmer
    ice rising from below and cooler ice sinking. The plain has almost no impact
    craters, meaning it is constantly being resurfaced and is geologically young.
  </p>

  <!-- Skipped heading level: h2 above, h4 here (no h3) -->
  <h4>Mountains of ice</h4>
  <p>
    Bordering the plains are mountains rising as high as 3,500 metres. At Pluto's
    frigid temperatures, water ice behaves like rock, and these peaks are
    essentially mountains made of frozen water "floating" on a sea of softer
    nitrogen ice.
  </p>

  <h2>Ice volcanoes</h2>
  <p>
    Two large features, Wright Mons and Piccard Mons, may be cryovolcanoes —
    volcanoes that erupt slushy ice instead of molten rock. If confirmed, they
    would be some of the largest known ice volcanoes in the Solar System.
  </p>

  <!-- Low-contrast aside (color-contrast) -->
  <aside class="callout callout-fail">
    Pluto's thin atmosphere produces dozens of layers of blue haze, and may even
    create a faint nitrogen "snow" or frost that coats the highlands in white.
  </aside>
</Layout>
